05518nam a22009855i 9783110671315DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020935438  a97831106713157 a10.1515/97831106713152doi  a(DE-B1597)534725  a(OCoLC)1178769304  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aB105.A35bM37 2020 4aB105.A35bM37 2020 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a128/.41 aMartens, Judith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDoing Things Together :bA Theory of Skillful Joint Action /cJudith Martens. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (IX, 208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEpistemic Studies : Philosophy of Science, Cognition and Mind ,x2512-5168 ;v41  aDiss.cRuhr Universität Bochumd2018.00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction: A Multidimensional Understanding of Acting Together -- t2. The Automatic/Non-Automatic Divide -- t3. Control and Intentions in Individuals -- t4. Motor Control and Skillful Action -- t5. Planning Agency and Shared Agency -- t6. Joint Action and Interaction -- t7. Skillful Joint Action -- tReferences -- tSubject Index -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo understand many of our everyday joint actions we need a theory of skillful joint action. In everyday contexts we do numerous things together. Philosophers of collective intentionality have wondered how we can distinguish parallel cases from cases where we act together. Often their theories argue in favor of one characteristic, feature, or function, that differentiates the two. This feature then distinguishes parallel actions from joint action. The approach in this book is different. Three claims are developed: (1) There are several functions that help human agents coordinate and act together. (2) This entails that joint action should be understood through these different, interrelated, types of coordination. (3) A multidimensional conceptual space, with three levels of control and coordination, will allow us to connect these different forms of coordination and their interdependencies. This allows us to understand the jointness of an action in a more differentiated and encompassing way. This approach has ramifications for several distinctions that are typically understood to be binary, including those between action and mere bodily movement, joint action and parallel action, and action together and not together.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAction theory. 0aJoint attention. 4aKompetenz. 4aKoordination. 4agemeinsames Handeln. 4asoziale Interaktion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aCoordination.  aJoint Action.  aSkill.  aSocial Interaction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110704648oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831106713390 cprintz978311067017240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311067131540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110671315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110671315/original  a978-3-11-065906-1  De Gruyter Eng